SIMPLE: maniple
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Maniple
<hw>Man"i*ple</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>manipulus</ets>, <ets>maniplus</ets>, a handful, a certain number
of soldiers; <ets>manus</ets> hand + root of <ets>plere</ets> to fill,
<ets>plenus</ets> full: cf. F. <ets>maniple</ets>. See <er>Manual</er>,
and <er>Full</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
handful.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A division of the Roman army numbering sixty men
exclusive of officers; any small body of soldiers; a company.</def>
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Originally, a napkin; later, an ornamental band or
scarf worn upon the left arm as a part of the vestments of a priest in
the Roman Catholic Church. It is sometimes worn in the English Church
service.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manipular</ent>⟦br⟧
